  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and frameworks to combat money laundering, including:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- An intergovernmental organization that sets global standards\n- Develops recommendations for preventing money laundering\n- Not a law itself, but influences national and international policies\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Provides guidelines for member states to combat money laundering\n- Encourages international cooperation in investigating financial crimes\n\n3. The Egmont Group\n- An international network of financial intelligence units\n- Facilitates information sharing between countries\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Provides guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering\n- Promotes international banking standards\n\n5. Individual Country Laws\n- Many countries have specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws\n- Examples include the U.S. Bank Secrecy Act and EU's Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n\nThese frameworks and laws require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nWhile there's no single comprehensive international law, these mechanisms work together to prevent and prosecute money laundering globally.",
